
CSS inset property
In CSS, if you want to set the top, bottom, left, and right properties of an element to the same value, you can use the inset property:

/* Instead of */
.myElement {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 0;
}

/* you can simply do */
.myElement {
  position: absolute;
  inset: 0;
}
It is also possible to set the four values separately, similarly to the margin or padding shorthand:

/* Instead of */
.myElement {
  position: absolute;
  top: 10px;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 10px;
  left: 0;
}

/* you can simply do */
.myElement {
  position: absolute;
  inset: 10px 0;
}

/* Instead of */
.myElement {
  position: absolute;
  top: 10px;
  right: 20px;
  bottom: 30px;
  left: 40px;
}

/* you can simply do */
.myElement {
  position: absolute;
  inset: 10px 20px 30px 40px;
}
